In TypeScript, you can tell the type system that you know that a value can have multiple types, but in practice, you know that it will only have one type by using a union type. 

For example, suppose you have an interface for a user:
```ts
interface User {
    id: number;
    name: string;
}
```
Now, suppose that you also have an interface for a customer:
```ts
interface Customer {
    id: number;
    name: string;
}
```
You could combine these two interfaces into one union type:
```ts
type UserOrCustomer = User | Customer;
```
This tells the type system that a value can be either a User or a Customer, but in practice, you know that it will only be one or the other.

